{"timestamp":1771853464242,"location":"generation","stage":"PHASE10_SCORE_FULL","data":{"lessonId":"203-SYM1A","total":82,"grade":"Needs rework","breakdown":{"beginnerClarity":28,"teachingBeforeTesting":25,"markingRobustness":20,"alignmentToLO":0,"命中QuestionQuality":9},"issueCount":4,"issues":[{"id":"AL-01","category":"Alignment to LO/AC","jsonPointers":["/blocks/3/content/content","/blocks/5/content/content"],"excerpt":"A Graphic Symbol is a simplified visual representation... A Schematic Diagram is a drawing that uses symbols...","problem":"The lesson content focuses entirely on electrical symbol logic and drawing types (Schematics vs. Wiring Diagrams) instead of identifying transmission and distribution voltages as required by the syllabus context.","whyItMatters":"The lesson fails to address the target Assessment Criteria (AC2 and AC3 of LO5), meaning students will not learn the specific voltage levels (e.g., 400kV, 11kV, 230V) required for the qualification.","alignmentGap":"AC2/AC3"},{"id":"AL-02","category":"Alignment to LO/AC","jsonPointers":["/metadata/syllabusAnchors"],"excerpt":"\"learningOutcome\": \"LO2\"","problem":"The lesson metadata targets LO2, but the syllabus requirement for this assessment is LO5 (How electricity is supplied).","whyItMatters":"Misaligned metadata leads to incorrect lesson sequencing and prevents the curriculum from covering the mandatory ACs for power supply distribution.","alignmentGap":"GENERAL PEDAGOGY"},{"id":"CL-01","category":"Beginner Clarity","jsonPointers":["/blocks/3/content/content"],"excerpt":"Misconception: Every time two lines cross on a drawing, they are connected. | Correction: Lines only represent a connection if a junction dot is present... | AC: AC2.3","problem":"The misconception block references 'AC2.3', but in the context of Unit 203 LO5, AC3 refers to 'Identify distribution voltages', which has nothing to do with junction dots.","whyItMatters":"Incorrect AC tagging in misconception blocks confuses instructors and makes it difficult to track which learning objectives are actually being supported.","alignmentGap":"AC3"},{"id":"CL-02","category":"Beginner Clarity","jsonPointers":["/blocks/6/content/questions/2"],"excerpt":"Why will a schematic fail to help you find a physical wire inside a wall?","problem":"While the lesson uses a good 'London Underground' analogy, it lacks a micro-scenario involving the actual target concepts: voltage measurement or scale.","whyItMatters":"Without micro-scenarios involving quantity or intensity (like voltage levels), technical lessons remain abstract and fail to prepare students for real-world measurement tasks.","alignmentGap":"GENERAL PEDAGOGY"}]},"sessionId":"generation"}
