{"timestamp":1772120776150,"stage":"STEP_3_FAILED","data":{"error":"Failed to parse quiz questions as JSON: Unexpected non-whitespace character after JSON at position 5301 (line 122 column 2)","debugInfo":{"rawResponse":"[\n  {\n    \"id\": 4051,\n    \"question\": \"A student observes a plastic duck floating on a pond as a series of water waves pass by. Which observation provides evidence that the waves transfer energy but not the water itself?\",\n    \"options\": [\n      \"The duck bobs up and down in the same position as the wave passes.\",\n      \"The duck travels across the pond at the same speed as the wave crests.\",\n      \"The duck moves in the opposite direction to the wave's energy transfer.\",\n      \"The duck remains perfectly still and does not move at all as the wave passes.\"\n    ],\n    \"correctAnswer\": 0,\n    \"misconceptionCodes\": {\n      \"1\": \"TOPOLOGY_CONFUSION\",\n      \"2\": \"OTHER\",\n      \"3\": \"OTHER\"\n    },\n    \"section\": \"Introduction to Waves\",\n    \"category\": \"Waves\",\n    \"tags\": [\"conceptual\", \"explanation\", \"terminology\"],\n    \"learningOutcomeId\": \"PHY-4.LO1.AC4.2\",\n    \"answerType\": \"mcq\",\n    \"difficulty\": 2,\n    \"estimatedTime\": 60,\n    \"explanation\": \"Evidence that waves do not transfer matter is seen when an object floating on the surface (like a duck or cork) moves up and down (perpendicular to the energy transfer) but does not move along with the wave.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"id\": 4052,\n    \"question\": \"Which of the following correctly describes the difference between longitudinal and transverse waves?\",\n    \"options\": [\n      \"In longitudinal waves, vibrations are parallel to energy transfer; in transverse waves, vibrations are perpendicular.\",\n      \"In transverse waves, vibrations are parallel to energy transfer; in longitudinal waves, vibrations are perpendicular.\",\n      \"Longitudinal waves can only travel through a vacuum, while transverse waves require a medium.\",\n      \"Transverse waves transfer matter across distances, while longitudinal waves only transfer energy.\"\n    ],\n    \"correctAnswer\": 0,\n    \"misconceptionCodes\": {\n      \"1\": \"CONFUSED_TERMINOLOGY\",\n      \"2\": \"OTHER\",\n      \"3\": \"TOPOLOGY_CONFUSION\"\n    },\n    \"section\": \"Introduction to Waves\",\n    \"category\": \"Waves\",\n    \"tags\": [\"discrimination\", \"terminology\", \"conceptual\"],\n    \"learningOutcomeId\": \"PHY-4.LO1.AC4.5\",\n    \"answerType\": \"mcq\",\n    \"difficulty\": 2,\n    \"estimatedTime\": 60,\n    \"explanation\": \"By definition, longitudinal waves (like sound) have oscillations parallel to the direction of energy transfer, whereas transverse waves (like EM waves) have oscillations at 90 degrees (perpendicular) to the direction of energy transfer.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"id\": 4053,\n    \"question\": \"A sound wave has a frequency of 500 Hz and a wavelength of 0.68 m. Calculate the velocity of this sound wave.\",\n    \"options\": [\n      \"340 m/s\",\n      \"735 m/s\",\n      \"0.00136 m/s\",\n      \"500.68 m/s\"\n    ],\n    \"correctAnswer\": 0,\n    \"misconceptionCodes\": {\n      \"1\": \"DIVIDED_INSTEAD\",\n      \"2\": \"DIVIDED_INSTEAD\",\n      \"3\": \"OTHER\"\n    },\n    \"section\": \"Introduction to Waves\",\n    \"category\": \"Waves\",\n    \"tags\": [\"calculation\", \"frequency\", \"units\"],\n    \"learningOutcomeId\": \"PHY-4.LO1.AC4.6b\",\n    \"answerType\": \"mcq\",\n    \"difficulty\": 3,\n    \"estimatedTime\": 75,\n    \"explanation\": \"Using the wave equation v = f × λ, we multiply the frequency (500 Hz) by the wavelength (0.68 m) to get 340 m/s.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"id\": 4054,\n    \"question\": \"A ship uses a sonar pulse to measure the depth of the ocean. The speed of sound in water is 1500 m/s. If the echo is detected 0.4 seconds after the pulse was sent, what is the depth of the seabed?\",\n    \"options\": [\n      \"300 m\",\n      \"600 m\",\n      \"3750 m\",\n      \"1500.4 m\"\n    ],\n    \"correctAnswer\": 0,\n    \"misconceptionCodes\": {\n      \"1\": \"OTHER\",\n      \"2\": \"DIVIDED_INSTEAD\",\n      \"3\": \"OTHER\"\n    },\n    \"section\": \"Introduction to Waves\",\n    \"category\": \"Waves\",\n    \"tags\": [\"application\", \"calculation\", \"units\"],\n    \"learningOutcomeId\": \"PHY-4.LO1.AC4.8P\",\n    \"answerType\": \"mcq\",\n    \"difficulty\": 3,\n    \"estimatedTime\": 90,\n    \"explanation\": \"Distance = speed × time. Total distance traveled by the pulse is 1500 m/s × 0.4 s = 600 m. Since the pulse travels to the seabed and back, the depth is half the total distance: 600 / 2 = 300 m.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"id\": 4055,\n    \"question\": \"When a sound wave travels from air into a solid concrete wall, which statement correctly describes the change in its properties?\",\n    \"options\": [\n      \"The velocity and wavelength increase, while the frequency remains the same.\",\n      \"The velocity and frequency increase, while the wavelength remains the same.\",\n      \"The velocity and wavelength decrease, while the frequency remains the same.\",\n      \"The velocity increases, but the frequency and wavelength both decrease.\"\n    ],\n    \"correctAnswer\": 0,\n    \"misconceptionCodes\": {\n      \"1\": \"CONFUSED_TERMINOLOGY\",\n      \"2\": \"OTHER\",\n      \"3\": \"TOPOLOGY_CONFUSION\"\n    },\n    \"section\": \"Introduction to Waves\",\n    \"category\": \"Waves\",\n    \"tags\": [\"discrimination\", \"conceptual\", \"terminology\"],\n    \"learningOutcomeId\": \"PHY-4.LO2.AC4.16\",\n    \"answerType\": \"mcq\",\n    \"difficulty\": 3,\n    \"estimatedTime\": 90,\n    \"explanation\": \"Sound travels faster in solids than in air. When a wave changes medium, its frequency is determined by the source and remains constant. Since v = f × λ, if velocity (v) increases and frequency (f) is constant, the wavelength (λ) must also increase.\"\n  }\n]]","parseError":"Unexpected non-white