{"timestamp":1772211485142,"location":"generation","stage":"PHASE10_SCORE_FULL","data":{"lessonId":"BIO-6-1B","total":94,"grade":"Ship it","breakdown":{"beginnerClarity":28,"teachingBeforeTesting":24,"markingRobustness":18,"alignmentToLO":15,"questionQuality":9},"issueCount":3,"issues":[{"id":"ISSUE_01","category":"Marking Robustness","jsonPointers":["/blocks/4/content/questions/2/expectedAnswer"],"excerpt":"\"expectedAnswer\": [\"high temperatures\"]","problem":"The question asks for a 'specific temperature range', but the expected answer is a vague qualitative description ('high temperatures').","whyItMatters":"This leads to grading ambiguity. A student might correctly answer 'above the optimum' or 'past the peak temperature', which are more precise than 'high' but might not match the narrow expected list.","alignmentGap":"AC6.3"},{"id":"ISSUE_02","category":"Beginner Clarity","jsonPointers":["/blocks/3/content/content"],"excerpt":"Rate of Reaction refers to how quickly a plant can take raw materials...","problem":"The lesson alternates between 'Rate of Reaction', 'Rate of Production', and 'Rate of Photosynthesis' without explicitly stating they are synonymous in this context.","whyItMatters":"Novice learners may struggle to realize that the general chemical term (Reaction) and the specific biological process (Photosynthesis) are referring to the same measurement on the graph.","alignmentGap":"GENERAL PEDAGOGY"},{"id":"ISSUE_03","category":"Teaching-Before-Testing","jsonPointers":["/blocks/7/content/questions/1"],"excerpt":"A manufacturing unit produces 85 units per hour... What was the output limit caused by the raw material before it was doubled?","problem":"The lesson teaches the concept of limiting factors qualitatively (cupcake liners), but does not provide a worked example of a numeric deduction to find a specific value.","whyItMatters":"Moving from a conceptual analogy to a numeric logic puzzle is a cognitive leap that requires a micro-scenario model to ensure the student understands how to extract the 'limit' value from a word problem.","alignmentGap":"GENERAL PEDAGOGY"}]},"sessionId":"generation"}
