,"excerpt":"consumer's intake point ... service head","problem":"The vocab defines the split at the 'intake point' while the explanation and diagram use 'service head'.","whyItMatters":"Beginners are sensitive to terminology shifts; using consistent terms for the same physical component reduces cognitive load.","alignmentGap":"GENERAL PEDAGOGY"}],"overallAssessment":"The lesson demonstrates excellent pedagogical structure with clear Recall -> Reasoning -> Integration pathways and effective use of concrete anchors like toasters and rods. While technically sound and highly readable, it relies on generic placeholders for the worked examples and misses the explicit 'ADS' terminology required by the syllabus. Minor improvements to marking robustness and terminology consistency would elevate it to a perfect score."},"candidate":{"total":95,"grade":"Ship it","syllabus":{"unit":"203","unitTitle":"Electrical installations technology","learningOutcome":"LO4","loTitle":"Requirements for earthing systems","assessmentCriteria":["AC1.1 Identify earthing system types","AC1.2 Identify ADS component parts","AC1.3 Identify exposed conductive parts"]},"breakdown":{"beginnerClarity":27,"teachingBeforeTesting":23,"markingRobustness":20,"alignmentToLO":15,"questionQuality":10},"issues":[{"id":"TBT-COLD-TERM","category":"teachingBeforeTesting","jsonPointers":["/blocks/11/content/questions/0/expectedAnswer"],"excerpt":"expectedAnswer: [\"CPC\", \"Circuit Protective Conductor\"]","problem":"The term 'CPC' or 'Circuit Protective Conductor' is introduced for the first time in the final Spaced Review block without appearing in the vocabulary or explanation sections.","whyItMatters":"Asking students to recall a technical abbreviation that hasn't been explicitly taught creates frustration and breaks the 'Teaching-Before-Testing' rule.","alignmentGap":"AC2"},{"id":"CLARITY-SCENARIO-DEPTH","category":"beginnerClarity","jsonPointers":["/blocks/5/content/content"],"excerpt":"Micro-scenario: If you are working on a remote farm far from other houses...","problem":"The micro-scenario provides a vocational context but lacks a concrete comparison of scale, intensity, or performance differences (e.g., comparing the resistance of a long cable run versus the local earth path).","whyItMatters":"Universal pedagogical standards require micro-scenarios to involve measurement, quantity, or performance differences to anchor abstract concepts to observable reality.","alignmentGap":"GENERAL PEDAGOGY"}],"overallAssessment":"The lesson is pedagogically strong, utilizing effective concrete anchors like the toaster fault and safety valve analogy to explain ADS. It follows a logical progression from recall to integration, though it introduces one technical term (CPC) in the review phase that was not previously taught."},"accepted":true,"reason":"Candidate improves on original (95 > 90) and meets threshold","improvement":5,"regressions":["teachingBeforeTesting 25->23"]},"sessionId":"generation"}
