PEN, TT, ADS) before the concrete anchor of the kettle/washing machine scenario.","whyItMatters":"Beginners anchor new concepts more effectively when they see the observable reality (the kettle) before the symbolic language (the acronyms).","alignmentGap":"GENERAL PEDAGOGY"},{"id":"2","category":"Beginner Clarity","jsonPointers":["/metadata/misconceptions"],"excerpt":"metadata.misconceptions","problem":"Valuable misconceptions (like the earth wire carrying current normally) are defined in metadata but not presented to the learner in an explicit content block.","whyItMatters":"Explicitly addressing misconceptions in the text is a primary tool for clarity; learners often carry the 'earth is a return path' error into their practice.","alignmentGap":"GENERAL PEDAGOGY"},{"id":"3","category":"Beginner Clarity","jsonPointers":["/blocks/5"],"excerpt":"Identifying the Three Main Earthing Systems","problem":"The lesson lacks micro-scenarios involving performance differences (e.g., comparing the safety 'speed' or 'intensity' of the fault path between a TT rod and a TN-C-S PEN).","whyItMatters":"Standard A requires scenarios involving scale or performance differences to move beyond simple visual identification into conceptual understanding.","alignmentGap":"AC1"}],"overallAssessment":"This is a high-quality introductory lesson that successfully isolates AC1, AC2, and AC3. It uses excellent concrete anchors and maintains a clear progression from recall to reasoning. Clarity would be further enhanced by moving the concrete scenarios earlier and explicitly surfacing the misconceptions defined in the metadata."},"accepted":true,"reason":"Candidate improves on original (95 > 87) and meets threshold","improvement":8,"regressions":["beginnerClarity 26->25"]},"sessionId":"generation"}
